<h1>Example 1</h1>

<section>
	<p class="example-intro">The comma is a common culprit responsible for the creation of run-on sentences.Commas are important tools for creating compound and complex sentences, but they must be used correctly. The following examples demonstrate the common errors in comma usage that lead to run-on sentences.</p>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">The patient was discharged from the hospital and the outpatient rehabilitation phase of treatment began.  <span class="red">RUN-ON SENTENCE!</span></h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">This example is a run-on sentence because it combines two independent clauses with a coordinating conjunction without the use of a comma. When we use a coordinating conjunction to combine two sentences, it <b>must</b> be preceded by a comma.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">The patient was discharged from the hospital, and the outpatient rehabilitation phase of treatment began. <span class="green">SENTENCE!</span></h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">There we go! We've fixed the run-on sentence by supplying the necessary comma before our coordinating conjunction. Remember, this isn't the only way to fix this run-on. We also could have split the two independent clauses into two seperate sentences like this: <i>The patient was discharged from the hospital. The outpatient rehabilitation phase of treatment began.</i></p>
	<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">It was important that every nurse be comfortable with the computer system, they had special classes to help new staff members learn the system. <span class="red">RUN-ON SENTENCE!</span></h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">Here we see an error so common it has an entire unit dedicated to it, the comma splice. What makes this example a run-on is that it tries to use a comma alone to combine two independent clauses. With independent clauses, a comma by itself isn't enough, we also need a coordinating conjunction.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">It was important that every nurse be comfortable with the computer system, and they had special classes to help new staff members learn the system. <span class="green">SENTENCE!</span></h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">Much better. This time we add the coordinating conjunction, <b>and</b>, and our run-on becomes a complete sentence. Again, we also could have divided the run-on into two seperate complete sentences: <i>It was important that every nurse be comfortable with the computer system. They had special classes to help new staff members learn the system.</i></p>
